<HTTPHeadersReferrer-Policy>
<summary>
The <strong><c>Referrer-Policy</c></strong> <see href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Glossary/HTTP header">HTTP header</see> controls how much <see href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/Security/Referer_header:_privacy_and_security_concerns">referrer information</see> (sent with the <see href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Headers/Referer">Referer</see> header) should be included with requests. Aside from the HTTP header, you can <see href="https://developer.mozilla.org#integration_with_html">set this policy in HTML</see>.
</summary>
<remarks>
<para>-<see href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/Security/Referer_header:_privacy_and_security_concerns">Web security &amp;gt; Referer header: privacy and security concerns</see><br/>-<see href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTTP_referer">HTTP referer on Wikipedia</see><br/>-When using <see href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Fetch_API">Fetch</see>: <see cref="Request.ReferrerPolicy."/><br/>-The obsolete <see href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Headers/Content-Security-Policy">Content-Security-Policy</see>'s <see href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Headers/Content-Security-Policy/referrer">Content-Security-Policy/referrer</see> {{deprecated_inline}} directive.<br/>-<see href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/Security/Same-origin_policy">Same-origin policy</see><br/>-<see href="https://blog.mozilla.org/security/2015/01/21/meta-referrer/">Tighter Control Over Your Referrers â€“ Mozilla Security Blog</see><br/></para>
